AGI - "I have broad shoulders", making the mayor receive "just, unjust, coming from several parts, in that last period mainly from parliamentarians of national character of the center, but honestly these two people have nothing to do and I do not see why they have to find themselves in a photo in national newspapers and in all broadcasts today, only because they asked the mayor to take a photograph in front of their store, as I happen, every day, with dozens". This was said by the mayor of Bari, Antonio&nbsp;Decaro, during a direct on social media where he explained that this morning he found his photograph with two women, relatives of boss Antonio Capriati, published in some national newspapers (Il Giornale e La Verità, ndr) "accostata al term 'mafia' and when I saw this photo, I wondered who were" the two women portrayed.
&nbsp;
After some calls to the former commander of the station of the Carabinieri of the old town of Bari and then to the former head of state police,&nbsp;Decaro&nbsp; called the parish priest of the Cathedral, Fr Franco Lanzolla, and "we understood all together that they are two relatives of the boss Capriati, but they have nothing to do with the rest of the family": "Don Franco told me - he explained&nbsp;Decaro&nbsp;- that the lady married a man with whom he ran a store, which then the shop behind this photograph, the daughter married a writer and she and her husband attend the parish of Don Franco, are part of the community of families". And concludes: "I am sorry to end up in a photograph where I am approached to the mob, but I also imagine the difficulty of these people who have nothing to do with it." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
"This morning we gave our full readiness to the inspection commission, which today came to present itself - said Decaro, talking about the arrival of the Antimafia Access Commission to the Municipality -. We have given them the documentation, everything that will be necessary, also because we have made a directive to all the directors of the divisions to make available to the committee. The city gates are wide open. We have always tried to work in compliance with rules and legality." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
In the live social, then, Decaro returned to explain the controversial episode told by the president of the Puglia Region, Michele Emiliano, from the stage of the event "Giù le mani da Bari". Emiliano recalled that he accompanied the current mayor at the home of boss Antonio Capriati's sister. The mayor who explained how 20 years ago he was a young engineer, called by Emiliano, then the first citizen of Bari, to take care of mobility. "One of the first themes I have dealt with was mobility in the old city," said&nbsp;Decaro via Facebook. "It was a time when there was wild parking, illegality, not only in the parking lot, but old Bari, twenty years ago was 'Scippolandia', there was an anti-Mafia magistrate (the mayor Emiliano, ndr) and a young councilman, taken from the fury of technicalism, who wanted to close the city, but it was not easy. They all got angry: the residents, the employees of the municipality, the shops of the city of the Murattiano center that parked there. Some people were also angry about criminal clans, because I don't think it was easy for them not to go in with the car or see the cameras coming up with the plates of those entering." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
Decaro&nbsp; he told that his activity lasted six months between those roads and that, in the first days, he happened to " meet people who mistreated me. There were guys big enough and one night, one of them would have approached him "the jacket, I don't know he had in his pocket. I said that the next day to Emiliano and a few days later, as we went to the cathedral, alone, we met this group of people and he in his own way, as an anti-Mafia magistrate, tells those people, 'Decaro&nbsp; you have to leave him alone, that is a young engineer, is working for me, serves the neighborhood, serves especially children, you see the children who are on the street, with the cars passing in front of the square'". From here the conclusion: "That was. I don't know what Emiliano remembers. I've never met anyone's sister to talk about this. I met so many people in the old town to try to find a solution that kept together the needs of residents, traders, we have made so many meetings." &nbsp;
&nbsp;

