AGI - "I was there with him, in that room of San Raffaele in Milan, in the early afternoon of Saturday, June 10, when he wrote these lines. And I will never forget." So Marina Berlusconi, daughter of FI leader, in the preface to the book by Paolo Del Debbio published by Corriere della Sera.
&nbsp;
"I visited him the previous night I saw him well. I came back the next day, I unfortunately found another man. Abandoned in an armchair, very affectionate, dark, suffering. He was accompanied by the chair at the table. He asked for paper and pen, asked the boss and began to write. I sat next to him and watched him work. At some point he stopped, he looked up, he fixed it in my eyes and said something that I will take into my last moment: 'See, Marina, life is like this: come, fai fai fai fai... And then you're gone."
&nbsp;
"Fini' the first page - continues the story of Marina Berlusconi - passed it, read it and fell the world on me. Because I realized that what he was writing was his ideal legacy, his will, the synthesis of convictions and values that had always accompanied him. He continued to write, and when he had finished he asked to be brought back to bed. I stayed there, pretending I didn't understand what we both understood very well."
&nbsp;
"That four pages I read them and read them tens of times, I turned them in my hands for hours, for days, and every time I miss my breath. I'm a very private memory, but I think it's right not just a private memory. They contain nothing unpublished, but I like to share them with those who loved my father, with those who believed in him and continue to believe in his ideas" he concludes.&nbsp;

